2. Monitor a Custom Resource (Example: RAM Usage)
Nagios doesn't monitor RAM by default in the basic config. Let’s add a check for your system memory to get a feel for the configuration files.

Define the Command:
Open the commands file:

Bash
sudo vi /usr/local/nagios/etc/objects/commands.cfg
Add this to the end of the file:

Code snippet
    define command {
        command_name    check_memory
        command_line    $USER1$/check_mem.pl -f -w 20 -c 10
    }
    ```

2.  **Add the Service to Localhost:**
    Open the localhost config:
    
```bash
    sudo vi /usr/local/nagios/etc/objects/localhost.cfg
    ```
    Add this service definition:
    
```nagios
    define service {
        use                     local-service
        host_name               localhost
        service_description     Memory Usage
        check_command           check_memory
    }
    ```
. Download the Missing Script
Run these commands to download a standard memory monitoring script and place it in the correct folder:

Bash
cd /usr/local/nagios/libexec/
sudo wget https://raw.githubusercontent.com/justintime/nagios-plugins/master/check_mem/check_mem.pl
2. Set the Correct Permissions
Nagios needs permission to execute this file, and it must be owned by the nagios user.

Bash
sudo chmod +x check_mem.pl
sudo chown nagios:nagios check_mem.pl
3. Test the Script Manually
Before checking the web dashboard, verify the script actually works from the command line:

Bash
./check_mem.pl -f -w 20 -c 10





3.  **Restart Nagios:**
    
```bash
    sudo systemctl restart nagios
    ```

